Reads a noweb markup stream on stdin and writes it to stdout,
replacing the body of every code chunk of known language with a
``minted`` environment.  Intended to run as the last filter of
``noweave``, after ``-index``.  See nowebfilters(7).
"""

import sys

<<constants>>
<<functions>>

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
@

\subsection{Mapping chunk names to lexers}

A root chunk in a tangleable literate program is conventionally named
after the file it produces, so the chunk name is our language oracle.
We recognize both bare filenames ([[fib.py]]) and the
LaTeX-safe quoted convention (the chunk name itself wrapped in noweb's double square
brackets), which we unwrap before matching.

The lookup has two levels.  First come two static tables, mapping
either an exact basename or an extension to a Pygments lexer name;
additional mappings can be supplied as command-line arguments
(Section~\ref{sec:main}).  Second, when the tables miss, we ask
Pygments itself, which knows the filename patterns of every
language it can highlight (next section).

Why keep tables at all, when Pygments already knows the answer?
Because Pygments need not be installed where \emph{this filter}
runs: the filter runs in the noweave pipeline, while Pygments is
only guaranteed wherever the woven document is later compiled, and
those can be different machines.  The tables keep the popular
languages working with no dependencies beyond Python itself.  They
also pin \emph{which} lexer alias we use where Pygments offers a
choice (e.g.\ [[perl]] rather than [[prolog]] for [[.pl]]), and
they are what the command-line mappings extend, so a user override
always beats Pygments' opinion.

