The quoting convention is unwrapped, then the basename is looked up,
first verbatim, then by extension, and finally against Pygments'
own filename patterns.  Returning [[None]] means ``no idea'', which
pass~1 may still resolve by inheritance.

<<functions>>=
def lexer_for_chunk(name):
    """Return the Pygments lexer for chunk ``name``, or None.

    The chunk name may use noweb's ``[[...]]`` quoting and may
    contain directory separators; only the basename decides.
    Names the built-in tables do not cover are matched against
    Pygments' filename patterns when Pygments is installed.
    """
    if name.startswith("[[") and name.endswith("]]"):
        name = name[2:-2]
    basename = name.rsplit("/", 1)[-1]
    if basename in LEXERS_BY_NAME:
        return LEXERS_BY_NAME[basename]
    dot = basename.rfind(".")
    if dot >= 0 and basename[dot:] in LEXERS_BY_EXT:
        return LEXERS_BY_EXT[basename[dot:]]
    return pygments_lexer_for_chunk(basename)
@

\subsection{Falling back on Pygments}
\label{sec:pygments}

Any language the tables miss can still be highlighted, provided
Pygments is importable where the filter runs.  Pygments maintains
exactly the mapping we need---filename patterns to lexers---for
every language it supports, and since Pygments is what eventually
does the highlighting, a lexer found this way is highlightable by
construction.  The import is guarded: when Pygments is absent, the
fallback silently reports no match and unknown languages keep
noweb's classic rendering, which is the same graceful degradation
the rest of the filter already practices.

<<constants>>=
try:
    from pygments.lexers import find_lexer_class_for_filename
except ImportError:
    find_lexer_class_for_filename = None
@

Of a found lexer we keep the \emph{first} alias.  Any alias would
select the same lexer, but the class names generated for the custom
lexer of Section~\ref{sec:lexer} are derived from the alias, so a
canonical choice keeps one wrapper class per language.

Each match scans Pygments' full pattern list and may import lexer
modules, so the result is memoized per basename.  The cache also
stores misses: the names that recur most---ordinary chunk names
like [[functions]], looked up once per use edge during
propagation---are exactly the ones that match nothing.

<<constants>>=
PYGMENTS_ALIASES = {}
@

<<functions>>=
def pygments_lexer_for_chunk(basename):
    """Return the alias of Pygments' lexer for ``basename``, or None."""
    if find_lexer_class_for_filename is None:
        return None
    if basename not in PYGMENTS_ALIASES:
        cls = find_lexer_class_for_filename(basename)
        PYGMENTS_ALIASES[basename] = (
            cls.aliases[0] if cls is not None and cls.aliases else None)
    return PYGMENTS_ALIASES[basename]
@

\subsection{Reading the markup stream}

Every line of the stream is [[@keyword]] optionally followed by a
space and an argument.  We keep the raw lines for verbatim passthrough
and parse them on demand; parsing returns [[None]] for a missing
argument so that callers can distinguish [[@text]] (no argument at
all) from [[@text ]] (empty argument).

<<functions>>=
def parse(line):
    """Split a markup line into (keyword, argument).

    The argument is None when the line is only ``@keyword``.
    """
    space = line.find(" ")
    if space < 0:
        return line[1:], None
    return line[1:space], line[space + 1:]
@

\subsection{Pass 1: chunk languages}
\label{sec:langs}

We scan the stream once to learn, for every code chunk, its name
([[@defn]]) and which chunks it uses ([[@use]]).  Chunks named like
filenames seed the language map; the languages then propagate along
the use edges, because a chunk included into a Python file contains
Python.  A chunk used from chunks of two different languages is
ambiguous, so we mark it conflicting and leave it unhighlighted
rather than guess wrong.

<<constants>>=
CONFLICT = object()
@

<<functions>>=
def chunk_languages(lines):
    """Compute chunk languages and string-embedded use sites.

    Returns a pair ``(langs, plain_uses)``.  ``langs`` maps chunk
    names to Pygments lexer names: languages are seeded from
    filename-like chunk names and propagated to the chunks they
    use, transitively; chunks with conflicting inherited languages
    are omitted.  ``plain_uses`` is the set of indices into
    ``lines`` of the ``@use`` lines that sit inside a Python
    string literal and must be rendered as plain text.
    """
    uses = {}
    langs = {}
    edges = []
    <<collect definitions, uses and string contexts>>
    <<propagate languages along use edges>>
    <<identify string-embedded use sites>>
    return ({name: lang for name, lang in langs.items()
             if lang is not CONFLICT},
            plain_uses)
@

A [[@defn]] names the chunk that the following lines (until
[[@end code]]) belong to, so we track the current chunk while inside
a code chunk and attribute every [[@use]] to it.

Alongside the use edges we track whether each use site sits inside
a string literal: per chunk name, we toggle a flag on every line
whose text contains an odd number of triple-quote delimiters.  The
state is kept per \emph{name} rather than per chunk instance
because noweb concatenates same-named chunks when tangling, so a
string opened in one instance is still open in the next.  Each use
is recorded twice: as an edge for the propagation, and---together
with its line index and string context---in [[edges]], from which
the plain-text use sites are computed once the languages are known.

<<collect definitions, uses and string contexts>>=
current = None
in_code = False
in_string = {}
for index, line in enumerate(lines):
    keyword, arg = parse(line)
    if keyword == "begin" and arg.startswith("code"):
        in_code = True
        current = None
    elif keyword == "end" and arg.startswith("code"):
        in_code = False
        current = None
    elif in_code and keyword == "defn":
        current = arg
        uses.setdefault(current, set())
        in_string.setdefault(current, False)
        lexer = lexer_for_chunk(current)
        if lexer is not None:
            langs[current] = lexer
    elif in_code and keyword == "text" and current is not None:
        flips = sum((arg or "").count(d) for d in STRING_DELIMITERS)
        if flips % 2:
            in_string[current] = not in_string[current]
    elif in_code and keyword == "use" and current is not None:
        uses[current].add((arg, in_string[current]))
        edges.append((current, arg, in_string[current], index))
@

The propagation is a straightforward worklist algorithm.  A chunk
whose own name determines a lexer keeps it: the explicit filename is
better information than inheritance, and skipping such chunks also
stops the propagation from crossing language boundaries between two
root files.

<<propagate languages along use edges>>=
worklist = list(langs)
while worklist:
    parent = worklist.pop()
    lang = langs[parent]
    if lang is CONFLICT:
        continue
    for child, embedded in uses.get(parent, ()):
        if lexer_for_chunk(child) is not None:
            continue
        if embedded and lang in PYTHON_LEXERS:
            inherited = "text"
        else:
            inherited = lang
        if child not in langs:
            langs[child] = inherited
            worklist.append(child)
        elif langs[child] is not CONFLICT and langs[child] != inherited:
            langs[child] = CONFLICT
@

\subsection{Chunk uses inside Python strings}
\label{sec:strings}

A literate Python program may put a docstring's text in a chunk of
its own:

\begin{verbatim}
def fib(n):
    """
    <fib docstring>
    """
    ...
\end{verbatim}
(angle brackets doubled in the real source).  Treating that use like
any other goes wrong twice.  First, the docstring chunk would
inherit the Python lexer and its prose would be highlighted as
code---words like [[for]] and [[is]] become keywords.  Second, the
reference itself cannot be rendered as a link there: Pygments lexes
the surrounding triple quotes as a single string token, and
minted's [[escapeinside]] is documented not to work inside string
and comment tokens, so the escaped link macros would leak verbatim
into the typeset string.

Both problems share one diagnosis---the use site sits inside an
open string literal---so the string tracking above fixes both.  A
chunk used inside a string in a Python chunk inherits the plain
[[text]] lexer instead of Python: it keeps minted's geometry and
font, but gets no token colouring.  And the use site itself is
rendered as literal noweb source syntax, which Pygments colours as
part of the string, instead of as an escaped link
(Section~\ref{sec:uses}).  The custom lexer of
Section~\ref{sec:lexer} lifts the latter limitation, at the cost
of a little setup.

The parity heuristic is deliberately naive: a triple quote inside a
comment or a single-quoted string fools it, and it does not
distinguish [[''']] from [["""]] when pairing delimiters.  Every
failure mode merely degrades to the behaviour without the
heuristic, and the common literate pattern---docstring delimiters
on their own lines around the use---is handled correctly.  The
heuristic is also Python-only: a chunk use inside a string literal
of another language goes undetected, so its escaped link macros can
leak into the typeset string just as described above.  Tracking
every language's string syntax is not worth the complexity when the
custom lexer of Section~\ref{sec:lexer} sidesteps the problem in
all languages at once.  The
conflict rule composes naturally: a chunk used both inside a
docstring and as real code inherits [[text]] and a code lexer,
conflicts, and falls back to noweb's classic rendering.

<<constants>>=
PYTHON_LEXERS = {"python", "python3", "py", "py3"}
STRING_DELIMITERS = ('"""', "'''")
@

<<identify string-embedded use sites>>=
plain_uses = set()
for parent, child, embedded, index in edges:
    if embedded and langs.get(parent) in PYTHON_LEXERS:
        plain_uses.add(index)
@

\subsection{Rendering chunk references}
\label{sec:uses}

Inside a highlighted body, a chunk reference must still look and
behave like noweb's \LA{}name~page\RA{}.  We reproduce exactly what
the [[totex]] backend emits for [[@use]]: the name (with noweb's
double-square-bracket quoting converted), followed by the sub-page tag of the
referenced definition, whose label [[noidx]] put in the [[@xref ref]]
line just before the [[@use]].  Because we emit the same macros,
the reference is rendered, hyperlinked, and page-numbered
identically to an unhighlighted chunk.

<<functions>>=
def render_use(name, label):
    """Return totex's LaTeX for a chunk reference inside code."""
    tex = "\\LA{}" + conv_quotes(name)
    if label is not None:
        tex += "~{\\nwtagstyle{}\\subpageref{" + label + "}}"
    return tex + "\\RA{}"
@

The two helpers below mirror [[TeXliteral]] and [[convquotes]] from
[[totex.nw]]; they must stay in sync with it so that a chunk name is
typeset the same whether or not its surroundings are highlighted.

<<constants>>=
TEX_SPECIALS = {
    "\\": "{\\nwbackslash}",
    "{": "{\\nwlbrace}",
    "}": "{\\nwrbrace}",
    "$": "{\\$}",
    "&": "{\\&}",
    "#": "{\\#}",
    "^": "{\\char94}",
    "_": "{\\_}",
    "%": "{\\%}",
    "~": "{\\char126}",
}
@

<<functions>>=
def tex_literal(text):
    """Escape ``text`` for LaTeX like totex's TeXliteral."""
    return "".join(TEX_SPECIALS.get(c, c) for c in text)
@

<<functions>>=
def conv_quotes(name):
    """Convert noweb's [[...]] quoting in a chunk name to LaTeX."""
    out = ""
    rest = name
    while True:
        head, sep, rest = rest.partition("[[")
        out += tex_literal(head)
        if not sep:
            return out
        inner, sep, rest = rest.partition("]]")
        if not sep:
            return out + tex_literal("[[" + inner)
        # Like totex, extra ]s before the closing ]] stay inside.
        while rest.startswith("]"):
            inner += "]"
            rest = rest[1:]
        out += "\\code{}" + tex_literal(inner) + "\\edoc{}"
@

\subsection{Pass 2: rewriting a code chunk}

A code chunk arrives as a header (everything from [[@begin code]] up
to and including the first [[@nl]], which carries the chunk name and
its cross-reference lines), a body of [[@text]]/[[@nl]]/[[@use]]
lines interleaved with index and cross-reference anchors, and a
trailer of [[@index]] lines that produce the ``Defines''
footers.  We keep the header and trailer---[[totex]] still renders
the chunk name, the ``used in'' notes, and the definition
lists---and replace only the body.

<<functions>>=
def rewrite_chunk(chunk, lang, out, start, plain_uses):
    """Rewrite one code chunk to use a minted environment.

    ``chunk`` is the list of raw markup lines from ``@begin code``
    through ``@end code``, beginning at index ``start`` of the
    stream; ``lang`` is the Pygments lexer name; ``plain_uses``
    holds the stream indices of string-embedded uses; the
    rewritten lines are appended to ``out``.
    """
    <<split off the chunk header>>
    <<assemble body lines, relocating anchors>>
    <<choose escape delimiters>>
    <<emit the minted environment>>
@

The header ends at the first newline of the chunk: [[noidx]] places
the chunk's own label, its definition line, and its
used-in/not-used cross-references all before that [[@nl]].

<<split off the chunk header>>=
position = 0
while position < len(chunk):
    line = chunk[position]
    out.append(line)
    position += 1
    if parse(line)[0] == "nl":
        break
@

\subsubsection{Relocating the invisible anchors}
\label{sec:anchors}

The body contains two kinds of content: the code itself ([[@text]],
[[@nl]], [[@use]]) and invisible anchors ([[@xref]] and [[@index]]
lines) that [[totex]] turns into hyperlink targets and index
entries.  We cannot leave the anchors interleaved with the code,
since the code becomes a single verbatim environment; dropping them
would break the identifier index, whose entries point at those
anchors.  Instead we move them after the environment.  They are
zero-width, and a sub-page reference resolves to the same page
whether the anchor sits on the first or the last line of the chunk,
so the index stays correct.

Anchors are buffered in [[held]] until we know what they belong to.
An [[@xref ref]] immediately before an [[@use]] is that reference's
target and is consumed by the inline rendering; an [[@xref label]]
immediately before such a reference is the use-site anchor, which
the LaTeX backend discards anyway, so we drop it.  Everything else
is flushed to [[relocated]] in its original order, preserving the
adjacency of [[@xref ref]]/[[@index]] pairs, which [[totex]]
interprets as a unit.

Each element of a body line is a tuple: [[("text", string)]] for raw
code, or [[("use", name, tex)]] for a chunk reference, carrying both
the rendered LaTeX and the plain chunk name so that the no-delimiter
fallback (next section) can still print something sensible.

<<assemble body lines, relocating anchors>>=
body = []
current_line = []
relocated = []
held = []
trailer = []
while position < len(chunk):
    line = chunk[position]
    keyword, arg = parse(line)
    if keyword == "end":
        trailer = chunk[position:]
        break
    elif keyword == "text":
        relocated.extend(held)
        held = []
        current_line.append(("text", arg or ""))
    elif keyword == "nl":
        relocated.extend(held)
        held = []
        body.append(current_line)
        current_line = []
    elif keyword == "use":
        label = None
        if held and (parse(held[-1])[1] or "").startswith("ref "):
            label = parse(held.pop())[1][len("ref "):]
            if held and (parse(held[-1])[1] or "").startswith("label "):
                held.pop()
        relocated.extend(held)
        held = []
        if CUSTOM_LEXER is None and start + position in plain_uses:
            current_line.append(("text", "@<<" + arg + "@>>"))
        else:
            current_line.append(("use", arg, render_use(arg, label)))
    else:
        held.append(line)
    position += 1
relocated.extend(held)
if current_line:
    body.append(current_line)
@

\subsubsection{Escape delimiters}

Minted's [[escapeinside]] option passes everything between two
delimiter characters straight to LaTeX; that is how the chunk
references keep their link macros.  Pygments splits the raw text on
the delimiters before lexing, so the mechanism works regardless of
the surrounding code.  The catch: the delimiter character must not
occur in the chunk's own code, or innocent code would be eaten as
LaTeX.  We therefore pick, per chunk, the first candidate character
that does not occur in any text part.  The candidates avoid every
character that is special to LaTeX, to keyval option parsing, or to
our own generated macros.  If a chunk defeats all candidates, we
degrade gracefully: references are rendered as plain
[[<<name>>]] text and a warning goes to standard error.

<<constants>>=
ESCAPE_CANDIDATES = "|!?;^&@:*+"
@

<<choose escape delimiters>>=
delimiter = None
if CUSTOM_LEXER is None and any(
        part[0] == "use" for line in body for part in line):
    code_text = "".join(part[1] for line in body
                        for part in line if part[0] == "text")
    for candidate in ESCAPE_CANDIDATES:
        if candidate not in code_text:
            delimiter = candidate
            break
    if delimiter is None:
        print("tominted: warning: no usable escape delimiter; "
              "chunk references will not be linked", file=sys.stderr)
@

\subsubsection{Emitting the environment}

The environment and the code are emitted as [[@literal]] lines,
which the backend copies verbatim into the document, each followed
by [[@nl]] so they land on lines of their own---\texttt{fancyvrb}
requires both the environment delimiters and the code to be in the
source line by line.  Finally the relocated anchors and the original
trailer follow.

One subtlety: the environment opens inside noweb's [[\nwbegincode]]
group, whose [[\setupcode]] and friends set up an almost-verbatim
regime that minted does not expect.  Three of its properties bite,
so the same [[@literal]] line that opens the environment first
restores a standard regime---locally to the group, so unhighlighted
chunks and the rest of the document are unaffected:

\begin{itemize}
\item The characters [[% ~ $ & # ^ _]] are made printable so code
      can contain them.  Minted's machinery and our escaped link
      macros assume the standard catcodes: with [[%]] printable,
      minted's generated comment characters typeset as stray [[%]]
      glyphs, and the [[~]] in a page tag prints as a literal tilde
      instead of a tie.
\item Newlines are made active, so that every newline ends a code
      line and blank lines show up blank.  Our auxiliary newlines
      around the environment would each typeset such an empty line,
      adding vertical space below the code; restoring the normal
      end-of-line catcode makes them harmless spaces.
\item Spaces are made active, so that runs of spaces survive in
      code.  An active space starts a paragraph, and when the list
      inside [[\begin{minted}]] then issues [[\par]], noweb's
      redefined [[\par]] turns that into a visible empty line above
      the code.  The reset must therefore be written \emph{entirely
      without spaces}: character codes are given numerically (the
      backtick is also active, so [[\catcode`\%]] would not parse),
      and every assignment is terminated by [[\relax]] instead of a
      space.  (Redefining [[\par]] instead is not an option; minted
      loops on a non-noweb [[\par]].)
\end{itemize}

<<constants>>=
CATCODE_RESET = (
    "\\catcode37=14\\relax\\catcode126=13\\relax"
    "\\catcode36=3\\relax\\catcode38=4\\relax"
    "\\catcode35=6\\relax\\catcode94=7\\relax"
    "\\catcode95=8\\relax\\catcode13=5\\relax"
)
@

The environment options make the highlighted chunk sit exactly like
a classic one.  Noweb indents code by [[\codemargin]] through
[[\leftskip]], but \texttt{fancyvrb} typesets its lines in a list of
its own that ignores the surrounding [[\leftskip]], so we pass the
same indentation explicitly as [[xleftmargin]].  The list normally
also inserts vertical space above and below the code
(\texttt{fancyvrb}'s [[vspace]], which defaults to [[\topsep]], plus
[[\partopsep]]); noweb's chunk layout has none, so both are zeroed.

<<constants>>=
LIST_SPACING_RESET = "\\partopsep=0pt\\relax"
ENV_OPTIONS = "xleftmargin=\\codemargin,vspace=0pt"
@

<<emit the minted environment>>=
options = ENV_OPTIONS
if CUSTOM_LEXER is None:
    lexer = lang
    if delimiter is not None:
        options += ",escapeinside={" + delimiter + delimiter + "}"
else:
    lexer = CUSTOM_LEXER + ":" + lexer_class(lang)
out.append("@literal " + CATCODE_RESET + LIST_SPACING_RESET
           + "\\begin{minted}[" + options + "]{" + lexer + "}")
out.append("@nl")
for line in body:
    parts = []
    for part in line:
        if part[0] == "text":
            parts.append(part[1])
        elif CUSTOM_LEXER is not None:
            parts.append(ESCAPE_LEFT + part[2] + ESCAPE_RIGHT)
        elif delimiter is not None:
            parts.append(delimiter + part[2] + delimiter)
        else:
            parts.append("@<<" + part[1] + "@>>")
    out.append("@literal " + "".join(parts))
    out.append("@nl")
out.append("@literal \\end{minted}")
out.append("@nl")
out.extend(relocated)
out.extend(trailer)
@

\subsection{Linked references inside strings: a custom lexer}
\label{sec:lexer}

The plain-text rendering of string-embedded references
(Section~\ref{sec:strings}) is the best that \emph{stock} Pygments
allows: its escape mechanism deliberately refuses to process
escapes inside string and comment tokens, because escape delimiter
characters can legitimately occur there in hand-written code.  Our
input is not hand-written, though---this filter generates it---so
that safety argument does not apply to us, and we can do better
with a small custom lexer.

Two observations make it work.  First, Pygments' LaTeX formatter
copies tokens of type [[Token.Escape]] into its output verbatim,
unconditionally---the safety filter lives in the lexer wrapper, not
in the formatter.  A lexer that emits [[Token.Escape]] for our
spans therefore injects working LaTeX from anywhere, including the
inside of a docstring.  Second, because we generate the input, we
can delimit those spans with Unicode private-use characters
(U+E000 and U+E001), which cannot occur in real code; the collision
risk that justifies Pygments' refusal is gone, and so is the need
to hunt for a safe delimiter per chunk.

The lexer subclasses Pygments' own escape-aware wrapper and
overrides exactly one method: the one that restricts escapes to
positions outside strings and comments.  Concrete classes wrap each
base lexer: [[NowebPythonLexer]] around [[python]],
[[NowebMakeLexer]] around [[make]], and so on.  They are generated
by a loop rather than written out, but they must exist eagerly in
the module namespace: [[latexminted]] runs the file with [[exec]]
and looks the class name up in the resulting dictionary, so a
module-level [[__getattr__]] (PEP~562) that creates classes on
demand is never consulted.  The loop covers every alias of every
lexer Pygments installs, so the wrapper classes can never lag
behind the filter's tables or its Pygments fallback
(Section~\ref{sec:pygments}); the classes are cheap because
[[type()]] does not import the wrapped lexer's module---that
happens only when minted instantiates a class.

A class name is the alias with every run of non-alphanumeric
characters treated as a word break, each word capitalized:
[[emacs-lisp]] becomes [[NowebEmacsLispLexer]].  The sanitization
must agree with [[lexer_class]] on the filter side, which computes
the same name when writing the minted environments.  Sanitized
names can collide, but only between aliases that differ solely in
non-alphanumeric characters ([[c++]] also maps to [[NowebCLexer]]);
the first alias encountered keeps the name.  The filter stays clear
of such collisions because its tables and its fallback pick
plain-word aliases like [[cpp]], which sanitize to themselves.

<<[[noweb_lexer.py]]>>=
"""Pygments lexers that render noweb chunk references everywhere.

These lexers wrap an ordinary Pygments lexer and turn spans
delimited by U+E000 and U+E001 into ``Token.Escape``, which the
LaTeX formatter copies into its output verbatim.  Unlike minted's
``escapeinside``, this also works inside strings and comments, so
noweb chunk references in Python docstrings keep their hyperlinks.
The delimiters are Unicode private-use characters that never occur
in real code; the input is generated by the tominted filter.

Use with minted as ``\\begin{minted}{noweb_lexer.py:NowebPythonLexer}``
(see nowebfilters(7) for the latexminted security setup).
"""

from pygments.formatters.latex import LatexEmbeddedLexer
from pygments.lexers import get_all_lexers, get_lexer_by_name

ESCAPE_LEFT = "\ue000"
ESCAPE_RIGHT = "\ue001"


class NowebEscapeLexer(LatexEmbeddedLexer):
    """Wrap ``base_lexer``, escaping U+E000...U+E001 spans anywhere."""

    base_lexer = "text"

    def __init__(self, **options):
        super().__init__(ESCAPE_LEFT, ESCAPE_RIGHT,
                         get_lexer_by_name(self.base_lexer, **options),
                         **options)

    def _find_safe_escape_tokens(self, text):
        # Unlike LatexEmbeddedLexer, process escapes everywhere,
        # including inside strings and comments.
        yield from self._find_escape_tokens(text)


def _class_name(alias):
    """Return the wrapper class name for ``alias``.

    Must compute the same name as the tominted filter's
    ``lexer_class``: non-alphanumeric runs are word breaks and
    every word is capitalized.
    """
    words = "".join(c if c.isalnum() else " " for c in alias).split()
    return "Noweb" + "".join(w.capitalize() for w in words) + "Lexer"


for _, _aliases, _, _ in get_all_lexers():
    for _alias in _aliases:
        _name = _class_name(_alias)
        if _name not in globals():
            globals()[_name] = type(_name, (NowebEscapeLexer,),
                                    {"base_lexer": _alias})
@

On the filter side, the custom lexer is enabled with
[[-lexer path]], where the path points at the tangled
[[noweb_lexer.py]] as the LaTeX compilation will see it (it is
written into the document, so it is relative to the directory where
[[pdflatex]] runs).  When enabled, \emph{every} chunk reference,
string-embedded or not, is emitted between the private-use
delimiters, the [[escapeinside]] option and the per-chunk delimiter
search are skipped, and the environments name the custom lexer
classes instead of the stock lexers.

<<constants>>=
CUSTOM_LEXER = None
ESCAPE_LEFT = "\ue000"
ESCAPE_RIGHT = "\ue001"
@

<<functions>>=
def lexer_class(lang):
    """Return the noweb_lexer.py class name wrapping ``lang``.

    Mirrors ``_class_name`` in noweb_lexer.py: non-alphanumeric
    runs are word breaks and every word is capitalized.
    """
    words = "".join(c if c.isalnum() else " " for c in lang).split()
    return "Noweb" + "".join(w.capitalize() for w in words) + "Lexer"
@

Minted treats loading custom lexer files as arbitrary code
execution---which it is---so [[latexminted]] only loads them when
the file name and its SHA-256 hash are whitelisted in a
[[.latexminted_config]] in the user's home directory (or
[[$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/latexminted/]], or [[TEXMFHOME]]):
\begin{verbatim}
{"custom_lexers": {"noweb_lexer.py": "<sha256 of the file>"}}
\end{verbatim}
The hash must be updated whenever [[noweb_lexer.py]] changes.

\subsection{Driving the rewrite}

The main loop buffers each code chunk and decides whether to rewrite
it.  The chunk's name is the argument of its first [[@defn]]; chunks
without a known language are copied verbatim, as are documentation
chunks and everything else in the stream.

<<functions>>=
def rewrite_stream(lines, langs, plain_uses):
    """Return the rewritten markup stream as a list of lines."""
    out = []
    i = 0
    while i < len(lines):
        line = lines[i]
        keyword, arg = parse(line)
        if keyword == "begin" and arg.startswith("code"):
            start = i
            chunk = []
            while True:
                chunk.append(lines[i])
                keyword, arg = parse(lines[i])
                i += 1
                if keyword == "end" and arg.startswith("code"):
                    break
            name = next((parse(l)[1] for l in chunk
                         if parse(l)[0] == "defn"), None)
            lang = langs.get(name)
            if lang is None:
                out.extend(chunk)
            else:
                rewrite_chunk(chunk, lang, out, start, plain_uses)
        else:
            out.append(line)
            i += 1
    return out
@

\subsection{The main program}
\label{sec:main}

Additional lexer mappings can be passed as arguments of the form
[[.ext=lexer]] or [[name=lexer]], e.g.\
[[-filter 'tominted .rs=rust']].  Keys starting with a dot extend
the extension table, all others the basename table.

<<functions>>=
def main():
    """Filter a noweb markup stream from stdin to stdout."""
    global CUSTOM_LEXER
    arguments = sys.argv[1:]
    while arguments:
        argument = arguments.pop(0)
        if argument == "-lexer":
            if not arguments:
                print("tominted: -lexer requires a path",
                      file=sys.stderr)
                sys.exit(1)
            CUSTOM_LEXER = arguments.pop(0)
            continue
        key, sep, value = argument.partition("=")
        if not sep:
            print("tominted: unknown argument:", argument,
                  file=sys.stderr)
            sys.exit(1)
        if key.startswith("."):
            LEXERS_BY_EXT[key] = value
        else:
            LEXERS_BY_NAME[key] = value
    lines = sys.stdin.read().split("\n")
    if lines and lines[-1] == "":
        lines.pop()
    langs, plain_uses = chunk_languages(lines)
    for line in rewrite_stream(lines, langs, plain_uses):
        print(line)
@
